{"title_page": "Native New Yorker (song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Native New Yorker\n| cover      = Native New Yorker Odyssey.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Odyssey (band)|Odyssey]]\n| album      = Odyssey\n| B-side     = Ever Lovin' Sam\n| released   = November {{Start date|1977}}\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7 inch]], [[12-inch single|12 inch]]\n| recorded   = 1977<br>House Of Music, [[West Orange, New Jersey]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Disco]]<ref name=whitburn>{{cite book |title= Hot Dance/Disco: 1974-2003|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=193}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:29<br>5:35 (Disco version)\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Sandy Linzer]]\n* [[Denny Randell]]\n| producer   =\n* Charlie Calello\n* Sandy Linzer\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''Native New Yorker'''\" is a disco song written by [[Sandy Linzer]] and [[Denny Randell]]. It was first recorded in 1977 by [[Frankie Valli]] and released on his album ''[[Lady Put the Light Out]]''. Later in 1977 the song became a hit single for the soul dance band [[Odyssey (band)|Odyssey]], which reached No. 3 on the U.S. disco chart.<ref name=whitburn/> Odyssey's \"Native New Yorker\" also went to No. 6 on the soul chart and No. 21 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=437}}</ref> It reached No. 5 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 404}}</ref>\n\nOdyssey recorded the song at House of Music, a private recording studio on Pleasant Valley Way in West Orange, New Jersey. Jeffrey Kawalek was the recording and mix engineer. Richard Tee played its signature piano track.  Jim Bonnefond assisted on many sessions.  Studio owner Charlie Conrad did additional engineering with Milton Galfas as his assistant engineer, and added additional instrumental solos to the original mixes to create extended dance versions. Sandy Linzer added Tommy Mandel on Clavinet and played Hair Drum himself, on the mix that would be released as a single, engineered by Billy Radice at Sigma in New York City. \n\nIt was also recorded by  [[Esther Phillips]] in 1978, and [[Black Box (band)|Black Box]] in 1998.\n\nThe song was later sampled by [[Rich Cronin]]'s band, Loose Cannons, for their song \"New York City Girls,\" as well as the house music group, Kluster, in their song featuring [[Ron Carroll]], entitled \"My Love\".\n\nThe [[tenor saxophone]] solo is played by [[Michael Brecker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saxophonemes.fr/eng.saxophonemes.fr/Pop_Saxophone.html |title=Pop Saxophone |publisher=Saxophonemes.fr |date= |accessdate=2014-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://seanfreemanmusic.com/transcripts/native-new-yorker-michael-brecker-solo-transcription/ |title=\"Native New Yorker\" Michael Brecker Solo Transcription |publisher=Seanfreemanmusic.com |date=2013-10-17 |accessdate=2014-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1977-78)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canada [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|7|song=Native New Yorker|accessdate=August 23, 2018}}\n|-\n|New Zealand ([[RIANZ]])<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20rianz&qsongid=2440#n_view_location Flavour of New Zealand, 7 May 1978]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Hot Dance Club Play]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot Soul Singles]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe song is featured in an episode of ''[[Good Times]]'', \"That's Entertainment, Evans Style\" (1978), as well as the films ''[[Eyes of Laura Mars]]'' (1978); ''[[54 (film)|54]]'' (1998); ''[[A Guide to Recognizing Your Saints]]'' (2006); ''[[The Nanny Diaries (film)|The Nanny Diaries]]'' (2007), and a commercial for ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' (2014). It also served as background music towards the end of the preliminary swimsuit segment of the 1981 [[Miss Universe]] pageant in [[New York City]]. The song is typically played during lead-in segments of ''[[Good Day New York]]''.\n\n\"Native New Yorker\" is played after every [[New York City FC]] soccer game at [[Yankee Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kessler|first1=Jordan|title=Hudson River Blue talks with DJ Mode, music director for New York City FC|url=https://www.hudsonriverblue.com/2015/8/12/9132521/dj-mode-nycfc-music-director-city-beats-yankee-stadium|website=Hudson River Blue|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=March 14, 2018|date=August 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|odyssey|native-new-yorker}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{YouTube|1TbJz_5D3s4|Listen to \"Native New Yorker\"}} (Frankie Valli)\n* {{YouTube|hGVEExb1YMI|Listen to \"Native New Yorker\"}} (Odyssey)\n\n{{The Four Seasons}}\n{{Odyssey (band)}}\n\n[[Category:1977 singles]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about New York City]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sandy Linzer]]\n[[Category:1977 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Denny Randell]]\n[[Category:Odyssey (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Frankie Valli songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Native New Yorker\n| cover      = Native New Yorker Odyssey.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Odyssey (band)|Odyssey]]\n| album      = Odyssey\n| B-side     = Ever Lovin' Sam\n| released   = November {{Start date|1977}}\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7 inch]], [[12-inch single|12 inch]]\n| recorded   = 1977<br>House Of Music, [[West Orange, New Jersey]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Disco]]<ref name=whitburn>{{cite book |title= Hot Dance/Disco: 1974-2003|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=193}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:29<br>5:35 (Disco version)\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Sandy Linzer]]\n* [[Denny Randell]]\n| producer   =\n* Charlie Calello\n* Sandy Linzer\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''Native New Yorker'''\" is a disco song written by [[Sandy Linzer]] and [[Denny Randell]]. It was first recorded in 1977 by [[Frankie Valli]] and released on his album ''[[Lady Put the Light Out]]''. Later in 1977 the song became a hit single for the soul dance band [[Odyssey (band)|Odyssey]], which reached No. 3 on the U.S. disco chart.<ref name=whitburn/> Odyssey's \"Native New Yorker\" also went to No. 6 on the soul chart and No. 21 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=437}}</ref> It reached No. 5 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 404}}</ref>\n\nOdyssey recorded the song at House of Music, a private recording studio on Pleasant Valley Way in West Orange, New Jersey. Jeffrey Kawalek was the recording and mix engineer. Richard Tee played its signature piano track.  Jim Bonnefond assisted on many sessions.  Studio owner Charlie Conrad did additional engineering, and added additional instrumental solos to the original mixes to create extended dance versions. Sandy Linzer added Tommy Mandel on Clavinet and played Hair Drum himself, on the mix that would be released as a single, engineered by Billy Radice at Sigma in New York City. \n\nIt was also recorded by  [[Esther Phillips]] in 1978, and [[Black Box (band)|Black Box]] in 1998.\n\nThe song was later sampled by [[Rich Cronin]]'s band, Loose Cannons, for their song \"New York City Girls,\" as well as the house music group, Kluster, in their song featuring [[Ron Carroll]], entitled \"My Love\".\n\nThe [[tenor saxophone]] solo is played by [[Michael Brecker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://saxophonemes.fr/eng.saxophonemes.fr/Pop_Saxophone.html |title=Pop Saxophone |publisher=Saxophonemes.fr |date= |accessdate=2014-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://seanfreemanmusic.com/transcripts/native-new-yorker-michael-brecker-solo-transcription/ |title=\"Native New Yorker\" Michael Brecker Solo Transcription |publisher=Seanfreemanmusic.com |date=2013-10-17 |accessdate=2014-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1977-78)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canada [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|7|song=Native New Yorker|accessdate=August 23, 2018}}\n|-\n|New Zealand ([[RIANZ]])<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20rianz&qsongid=2440#n_view_location Flavour of New Zealand, 7 May 1978]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]\n| style=\"text-align:center