 style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Washtenaw County, Michigan|Washtenaw]]\n|826\n|25\n|370,963\n|223\n|7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne]]\n|13,002\n|981\n|1,753,893\n|741\n|56\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Wexford County, Michigan|Wexford]]\n|7\n|1\n|33,466\n|21\n|3\n|- style=\"background:#bee8ff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Michigan Department of Corrections|MDOC]]{{ref label|Note3|c|c}}\n|486\n|12\n|38,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwjnewsradio.radio.com/articles/news/michigans-prison-population-down-for-fifth-straight-year|title=Michigan's Prison Population Down For Fifth Straight Year|date=December 20, 2019|website=WWJ Newsradio 950}}</ref>\n|1,279\n|32\n|- style=\"background:#bee8ff;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Federal Correctional Institution, Milan|FCI Milan]]{{ref label|Note4|d|d}}\n|39\n|0\n|1,600\n|2,438\n|0\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Out-of-State{{ref label|Note5|e|e}}\n|144\n|2\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Unknown\n|76\n|4\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|N/A\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |29,263\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |2,093\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n\n<small>Notes:<br>\n{{Note label|Note1|a|a}}Michigan.gov information is updated daily at 3 p.m., with COVID-19 results included as of 10 a.m..<br>\n{{Note label|Note2|b|b}}Deaths must be reported by health care providers, medical examiners/coroners, and recorded by local health departments in order to be counted.<br>\n{{Note label|Note3|c|c}}[[Michigan Department of Corrections]]<br>\n{{Note label|Note4|d|d}}[[Federal Correctional Institution]]<br>\n{{Note label|Note5|e|e}}Patients are not residents, but are being treated within the state of Michigan.<br>\n{{Note label|Note6|f|f}}Recovery total is only updated on Fridays</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.michigan.gov/coronavirus Coronavirus information] from the State of Michigan\n* [https://www.mlive.com/news/jackson/2020/03/updated-maps-michigan-coronavirus-cases-and-exposure-sites.html Updated maps: Michigan coronavirus cases and exposure sites] from MLive.com\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Michigan]]\n[[Category:2020 in Michigan|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Health in Michigan]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "TomCat4680", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical response", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Debuccalization", "text_new": "{{Short description|Sound change towards glottal articulation}}{{Refimprove|date=April 2013}}\n{{Sound change}}\n{{IPA notice}}\n\n'''Debuccalization''' is a [[sound change]] or [[alternation (linguistics)|alternation]] in which an oral [[consonant]] loses its original [[place of articulation]] and moves it to the [[glottis]] (usually {{IPAblink|h}}, {{IPAblink|\u0266}}, or {{IPAblink|\u0294}}).<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|O'Brien|2012|p=2}}</ref> The pronunciation of a consonant as {{IPA|[h]}} is sometimes called aspiration but in [[phonetics]], [[aspirated consonant|aspiration]] is the burst of air accompanying a [[stop consonant|stop]]. The word comes from [[Latin]] {{lang|la|bucca}}, meaning \"cheek\" or \"mouth\".\n\nDebuccalization is usually seen as a sub-type of [[lenition]], often defined as a consonant mutation involving the weakening of a consonant by progressive shifts in pronunciation. As with other forms of lenition, debuccalization may be [[synchrony and diachrony|synchronic or diachronic]] (i.e., it may involve alternations within a language [[allophone|depending on context]] or sound changes across time).\n\nDebuccalization processes occur in many different types of environments such as the following:<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|O'Brien|2012|pp=8\u201310}}</ref>\n* word-initially, as in [[Kannada language|Kannada]]\n* word-finally, as in [[Burmese language|Burmese]]\n* intervocalically, as in a number of [[English language|English]] varieties (e.g. ''litter'' {{IPA|[\u02c8l\u026a\u0294\u0259]}})\n\n==Glottal stop==\n===Arabic===\n{{IPA|/q/}} is debuccalized to {{IPA|/\u0294/}} in several Arabic varieties, such as northern [[Egyptian Arabic|Egyptian]], [[Lebanese Arabic|Lebanese]], western [[Syrian Arabic|Syrian]], and urban [[Palestinian Arabic|Palestinian]] dialects, partially also in [[Jordanian Arabic]] (especially by female speakers).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bassiouney|first=Reem|title=Arabic Sociolinguistics|publisher=Georgetown University Press|year=2009|isbn=978-1-58901-573-9|location=Washington, DC|pages=158-161}}</ref> The [[Maltese language]], which was originally an Arabic dialect, also shows this feature.\n\n===British and American English===\nMost English-speakers in England and many speakers of [[American English]] debuccalize {{IPA|/t/}} to a glottal stop {{IPA|[\u0294]}} in two environments: in word-final position before another consonant (American English IPA)\n*''get ready'' {{IPA|[\u02c8\u0261\u025b\u0294\u02c8\u0279\u025b\u027ei]}}\n*''not much'' {{IPA|[\u02c8n\u0251\u0294\u02c8m\u028ct\u0283]}}\n*''not good'' {{IPA|[\u02c8n\u0251\u0294\u02c8\u0261\u028ad\u031a]}}\n*''it says'' {{IPA|[\u026a\u0294\u02c8s\u025bz]}}\n\nand before a [[syllabic consonant|syllabic]] {{IPA|[n\u0329]}} following {{IPA|/l/}}, {{IPA|/r/}}, {{IPA|/n/}}, or a vowel. Here the {{IPA|/t/}} may also be [[nasal release|nasally released]]. (American English IPA)\n*''Milton'' {{IPA|[\u02c8m\u026al\u0294n\u0329]}}\n*''Martin'' {{IPA|[\u02c8m\u0251\u0279\u0294n\u0329]}}\n*''mountain'' {{IPA|[\u02c8m\u00e6\u028an\u0294n\u0329]}}\n*''cotton'' {{IPA|[\u02c8k\u02b0\u0251\u0294n\u0329]}}\n*''Latin'' {{IPA|[\u02c8l\u00e6\u0294n\u0329]}}\n\n===Cockney English===\nIn [[Cockney#Typical features|Cockney English]], {{IPA|/t/}} is often realized as a glottal stop {{IPA|[\u0294]}} between vowels, liquids and nasals (notably in the word ''bottle''), a process called [[t-glottalization]].\n\n===German===\nIn [[German language|German]], voiceless stops are commonly debuccalized before syllabic nasals in the following clusters: {{IPA|/mpm\u0329, ltn\u0329, ntn\u0329, \u014bk\u014b\u030d/}}, which thus become {{IPA|[m\u0294m\u0329, l\u0294n\u0329, n\u0294n\u0329, \u014b\u0294\u014b\u030d]}}. For example, {{lang|de|Lumpen}} (\u201crags, tatters\u201d) is pronounced {{IPA|[l\u028am\u0294m\u0329]}}. In some dialects, debuccalization may also occur before syllabic {{IPA|[l\u0329]}}, though this is less common.\n\nVoiced stops are not usually debuccalized. However, many [[Upper German]] and [[East Central German]] dialects merge voiced and unvoiced stops at least word-internally  and these merged consonants will be debuccalized. Thus in [[Bavarian language|Bavarian]], {{lang|bar|Anten}} (\u201cducks\u201d) and {{lang|bar|Anden}} (\u201cAndes\u201d) are both pronounced {{IPA|[\u02c8\u0251n\u0294n\u0329]}}. Speakers are often unaware of this.\n\n==Glottal fricative==\n===Slavey===\nAll coda consonants in [[Slavey language|Slavey]] must be glottal. When a non-glottal consonant would otherwise be positioned in a syllable coda, it debuccalizes to {{IPA|[h]}}:<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Smith|2008|p=527}}</ref>\n*{{IPA|/ts\u2019ad/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[ts\u2019ah]}} ('hat')\n*{{IPA|/xaz/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[xah]}} ('scar')\n*{{IPA|/tl\u2019u\u026e/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[tl\u2019uh]}} ('rope')\n\n===Scots/Scottish English===\nIn some varieties of [[Scots language|Scots]] (and [[Scottish English]]), particularly on the West coast, a non word-final {{IPA|/\u03b8/}} ''th'' shifted to {{IPA|[h]}}, a process called [[th-debuccalization]]. For example, {{IPA|/\u03b8\u026an/}} is realised as {{IPA|[h\u026an]}}.\n\n===Proto-Greek===\nIn [[Proto-Greek language|Proto-Greek]], {{IPA|/s/}} shifted to {{IPA|[h]}} initially and between [[sonorant]]s ([[vowel]]s, [[liquid consonant|liquids]] and [[nasal consonant|nasal]]s).\n* [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] {{wikt-lang|ine-x-proto|*sept\u1e3f\u0325}} \u2192 [[Ancient Greek]] {{transl|grc|hept\u00e1}} ({{wikt-lang|grc|\u1f11\u03c0\u03c4\u03ac}}) \"seven\" (vs. [[Latin]] {{wikt-lang|la|septem}})\n\nIntervocalic {{IPA|/h/}} was lost by the time of [[Ancient Greek]], and vowels in [[hiatus (linguistics)|hiatus]] were [[synaeresis|contracted]] in the [[Attic Greek|Attic]] dialect.\n* post-PIE ''*\u01f5\u00e9nesos'' \u2192 Proto-Greek {{lang|grk-x-proto|*g\u00e9nehos}} \u2192 [[Ionic Greek|Ionic]] {{transl|grc|g\u00e9neos}} ({{lang|grc|\u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2}}) : [[Attic Greek|Attic]] {{transl|grc|g\u00e9nous}} ({{lang|grc|\u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2}}) \"of a race\"\n\nBefore a liquid or nasal, an {{IPA|/h/}} was assimilated to the preceding vowel in Attic-Ionic and [[Doric Greek|Doric]] and to the following nasal in [[Aeolic Greek|Aeolic]]. The process is also described as loss of {{IPA|/h/}} and subsequent lengthening of a vowel or consonant to keep the syllable the same [[syllable weight|length]] ([[compensatory lengthening]]).\n* PIE {{wikt-lang|ine-x-proto|*h\u2081\u00e9smi}} \u2192 Proto-Greek {{lang|grk-x-proto|*ehmi}} \u2192 Attic-Ionic {{transl|grc|\u0113m\u00ed}} ({{lang|grc|\u03b5\u1f30\u03bc\u03af}}) : Aeolic {{transl|grc|\u00e9mmi}} ({{lang|grc|\u1f14\u03bc\u03bc\u03b9}}) \"I am\"\n\n===Sanskrit===\nIn [[Sanskrit]], {{IPA|/s/}} becomes {{IPA|[h]}} (written {{transl|sa|\u1e25}} in transliteration) when [[pausa|utterance-final]], e.g., {{transl|sa|k\u0101\u0301mas}} \"erotic love\" becomes {{transl|sa|k\u0101\u0301ma\u1e25}}.\n\n===West Iberian===\n====Spanish====\n{{main|Spanish dialects and varieties#Debuccalization of coda /s/|l1=Spanish dialects and varieties: Debuccalization of coda /s/}}\nA number of [[Spanish language|Spanish]] [[Spanish dialects and varieties|dialects]] debuccalize {{IPA|/s/}} at the [[syllable coda|end]] of a [[syllable]] to {{IPA|[h]}} or {{IPAblink|\u0266}}.\n\n====Galician====\nIn many varieties of [[Galician language|Galician]] as well as in [[Castrapo|Galician-influenced Spanish]], the phoneme {{IPA|/g/}} may debuccalize ({{lang|gl|[[gheada]]}}) to {{IPAblink|h}} in most or all instances, though {{IPAblink|x}} and {{IPAblink|\u0127}} are also possible realizations. There is also an inverse [[hypercorrection]] process of older or less educated Galician speakers replacing the phoneme {{IPAslink|x}} of the Spanish language by {{IPA|[g]}}, what is called {{lang|gl|gueada}}.\n\n====Portuguese====\n[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] is much less affected by debuccalization, but it is especially notorious in its [[Brazilian Portuguese|Brazilian variety]].\n\nAll over Brazil, the phoneme {{IPA|/\u0281/}} (historically an alveolar trill {{IPA|/r/}} that moved to an uvular position) has a rather long inventory of allophones: {{IPA|[{{IPAplink|r}} {{IPAplink|\u0282|\u027b\u031d\u030a}} {{IPAplink|\u00e7}} {{IPAplink|x}} {{IPAplink|\u0263}} {{IPAplink|\u03c7}} {{IPAplink|\u0281}} {{IPAplink|\u0280}} {{IPAplink|\u0127}} {{IPAplink|h}} {{IPAplink|\u0266}}]}}. Only {{IPAblink|\u0263}} is uncommon. Few dialects, such as {{lang|pt|[[South Region, Brazil|sulista]]}} and {{lang|pt|[[Rio de Janeiro (state)|fluminense]]}}, give preference to voiced allophones; elsewhere, they are common only as coda, before voiced consonants.\n\nIn such dialects, especially among people speaking an educated variety of Portuguese, it is usual for the rhotic coda in the [[Syllable#Rime|syllable rhyme]] to be an alveolar tap, as in European Portuguese and many registers of Spanish, or to be realized as {{IPAblink|\u03c7}} or {{IPAblink|x}}. In the rest of the country, it is generally realized as {{IPAblink|h}}, even among speakers not normally using this allophone or deleting it entirely, as is common in the vernacular.\n\nHowever, in some {{lang|pt|[[Minas Gerais|mineiro]]}}- and {{lang|pt|mineiro}}-influenced {{lang|pt|fluminense}} rural registers, {{IPA|[h]}} is used but as an allophone of {{IPAslink|l}} (rhotic consonants are most often deleted), a {{lang|pt|mar-mal}} merger, instead of the much more common and less stigmatized [[L-vocalization#Portuguese|{{lang|pt|mau-mal|nocat=yes}} merger]] characteristic of all Brazilian urban centers except for those bordering [[Mercosur]] countries, where coda {{IPAblink|\u026b}} was preserved, and the entire [[North Region, Brazil|North]] and [[Northeast Region, Brazil|Northeast]] regions. Its origin is the replacement of indigenous languages and {{lang|pt|[[l\u00edngua geral|l\u00ednguas gerais]]}} by Portuguese,{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}} which created {{IPAblink|\u0279}}, {{IPAblink|\u027b}} and [[r-colored vowel]] as allophones of both {{IPA|/\u027e/}} (now mostly {{IPA|/\u0281/}}) and {{IPA|/l/}} (now mostly {{IPA|[{{IPAplink|w|u\u032f}} ~ {{IPAplink|\u028a|\u028a\u032f}}]}}) phonemes in the coda since Natives could not easily pronounce them ([[caipira dialect]]).{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}} The later Portuguese influence from other regions made those allophones become rarer in some areas, but the {{lang|pt|mar-mal}} merger did not disappear in a few isolated villages and towns.\n\nFinally, many {{lang|pt|fluminense}} registers, especially those of the poor and of the youth, most northern and northeastern dialects, and, to a much minor degree, all other Brazilian dialects, debuccalize {{IPA|/s/}} (that is, {{IPA|[\u0255 ~ \u0291]}}) but less so than in Spanish. However, a {{lang|pt|mar-mas}} merger or even a {{lang|pt|mar-mais}} merger occurs: {{lang|pt|mas mesmo assim}} \"but even so\" or {{lang|pt|mas mesma, sim}} \"though, right, the same (f) one\" {{IPA|[m\u0250\u0266 \u02c8me\u0266m\u0259 \u02c8s\u0129]}}; {{lang|pt|mais}} light \"lighter, more slim\", or also \"less caloric/fatty\" {{IPA|[\u02c8ma\u0266 \u02c8lajt\u0255]}}; {{lang|pt|mas de mim, n\u00e3o}} \"but from me, no\" or {{lang|pt|mais de mim, n\u00e3o}} \"not more from me\" {{IPA|[\u02c8ma\u0266 d\u0291i \u02c8m\u0129 \u02c8n\u025c\u0303w]}}. A coda rhotic in the Brazilian dialects in the [[Centro-Sul]] area is hardly ever glottal, and the debuccalized {{IPA|/s/}} is unlikely to be confused with it.\n\n===Romanian===\nIn the Moldavian dialect of [[Romanian language|Romanian]], {{IPAslink|f}} is debuccalised to {{IPA|[h]}} and so, for example, {{lang|ro|s\u0103 fie}} becomes {{lang|ro|s\u0103 hie}}. The same occurred in [[Old Spanish]], Old [[Gascon language|Gascon]] and [[Old Japanese]] and occurs today in [[Sylheti language |Sylheti]].\n\n===Goidelic Languages===\n{{main|Scottish Gaelic phonology#Lenition and spelling|Irish initial mutations|l1=Scottish Gaelic phonology: Lenition and spelling}}\nIn [[Scottish Gaelic|Scottish]] and [[Irish language|Irish Gaelic]], ''s'' and ''t'' changed by [[lenition]] to {{IPA|[h]}}, spelled ''sh'' and ''th''.\n\n==Loanwords==\nDebuccalization can be a feature of loanword phonology. For example, while [[Korean language|Korean]] allows certain coda obstruents, [[Japanese language|Japanese]] does not. Those consonants realized in Korean as unreleased voiceless stops ({{IPA|[p\u02fa t\u02fa k\u02fa]}}) may be realized in Japanese as glottal stops:<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Whang|2012|p=2}}</ref>\n*{{IPA|[t\u0255uk\u02fa]}} \u2192 {{IPA|[t\u0255u\u0294]}} ('porridge')\n*{{IPA|[mok\u02fa]}} \u2192 {{IPA|[mo\u0294]}} ('neck')\n*{{IPA|[mat\u02fa]}} \u2192 {{IPA|[ma\u0294]}} ('flavor')\n*{{IPA|[tap\u02fa]}}\u2192 {{IPA|[ta\u0294]}} ('tower')\n\nSimilarly, debuccalization can be seen in [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] loans into [[Selayar language|Selayar]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|O'Brien|2012|p=28}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{citation\n|last=O'Brien\n|first=Jeremy Paul\n|year=2012\n|title=An experimental approach to debuccalization and supplementary gestures\n|url=http://escholarship.org/uc/item/1cm694ff\n}}\n*{{citation\n|last=Smith\n|first=Jennifer L.\n|year=2008\n|chapter=X Markedness, faithfulness, positions, and contexts: Lenition and fortition in Optimality Theory\n|editor-last=de Carvalho\n|editor-first=Joaquim Brand\u00e3o\n|editor2-last=Scheer\n|editor2-first=Tobias\n|editor3-last=S\u00e9g\u00e9ral\n|editor3-first=Philippe\n|title=Lenition and Fortition\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ztksXfGwLVgC&dq=\n}}\n*{{citation\n\t|last=Whang \n\t|first=James Dy \n\t|year=2012 \n\t|title=Perception of Illegal Contrasts: Japanese Adaptations of Korean Coda Obstruents \n\t|journal=Proceedings of the 36th Annual Meeting of the Berkeley Linguistics Society \n\t|url=https://files.nyu.edu/jdw412/public/james.whang/main_files/Whang.pdf \n\t|url-status=dead \n\t|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624212809/https://files.nyu.edu/jdw412/public/james.whang/main_files/Whang.pdf \n\t|archivedate=2013-06-24 \n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=wx-4wmfQbVMC&pg=PA123&dq=debuccalization+1990&hl=en&ei=DNE-TuDdCrSisQLbsc0y&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=debuccalization%201990&f=false \"Debuccalization\"] (Chapter 4 of Paul D. Fallon's ''The Synchronic and Diachronic Phonology of Ejectives'' [Routledge, 2001]) gives many other terms that have been proposed for the phenomenon.\n* [http://people.ucsc.edu/~jpobrien/papers/obrien_qe.pdf Debuccalization and supplementary gestures]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:Phonology]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Sound change towards glottal articulation}}{{Refimprove|date=April 2013}}\n{{Sound change}}\n{{IPA notice}}\n\n'''Debuccalization''' is a [[sound change]] or [[alternation (linguistics)|alternation]] in which an oral [[consonant]] loses its original [[place of articulation]] and moves it to the [[glottis]] (usually {{IPAblink|h}}, {{IPAblink|\u0266}}, or {{IPAblink|\u0294}}).<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|O'Brien|2012|p=2}}</ref> The pronunciation of a consonant as {{IPA|[h]}} is sometimes called aspiration but in [[phonetics]], [[aspirated consonant|aspiration]] is the burst of air accompanying a [[stop consonant|stop]]. The word comes from [[Latin]] {{lang|la|bucca}}, meaning \"cheek\" or \"mouth\".\n\nDebuccalization is usually seen as a sub-type of [[lenition]], often defined as a consonant mutation involving the weakening of a consonant by progressive shifts in pronunciation. As with other forms of lenition, debuccalization may be [[synchrony and diachrony|synchronic or diachronic]] (i.e., it may involve alternations within a language [[allophone|depending on context]] or sound changes across time).\n\nDebuccalization processes occur in many different types of environments such as the following:<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|O'Brien|2012|pp=8\u201310}}</ref>\n* word-initially, as in [[Kannada language|Kannada]]\n* word-finally, as in [[Burmese language|Burmese]]\n* intervocalically, as in a number of [[English language|English]] varieties (e.g. ''litter'' {{IPA|[\u02c8l\u026a\u0294\u0259]}})\n\n==Glottal stop==\n===Arabic===\n{{IPA|/q/}} is debuccalized to {{IPA|/\u0294/}} in several Arabic varieties, such as northern [[Egyptian Arabic|Egyptian]], [[Lebanese Arabic|Lebanese]], western [[Syrian Arabic|Syrian]], and urban [[Palestinian Arabic|Palestinian]] dialects, partially also in [[Jordanian Arabic]] (especially by female speakers).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bassiouney|first=Reem|title=Arabic Sociolinguistics|publisher=Georgetown University Press|year=2009|isbn=978-1-58901-573-9|location=Washington, DC|pages=158-161}}</ref> The [[Maltese language]], which was originally an Arabic dialect, also shows this feature.\n\n===British and American English===\nMost English-speakers in England and many speakers of [[American English]] debuccalize {{IPA|/t/}} to a glottal stop {{IPA|[\u0294]}} in two environments: in word-final position before another consonant (American English IPA)\n*''get ready'' {{IPA|[\u02c8\u0261\u025b\u0294\u02c8\u0279\u025b\u027ei]}}\n*''not much'' {{IPA|[\u02c8n\u0251\u0294\u02c8m\u028ct\u0283]}}\n*''not good'' {{IPA|[\u02c8n\u0251\u0294\u02c8\u0261\u028ad\u031a]}}\n*''it says'' {{IPA|[\u026a\u0294\u02c8s\u025bz]}}\n\nand before a [[syllabic consonant|syllabic]] {{IPA|[n\u0329]}} following {{IPA|/l/}}, {{IPA|/r/}}, {{IPA|/n/}}, or a vowel. Here the {{IPA|/t/}} may also be [[nasal release|nasally released]]. (American English IPA)\n*''Milton'' {{IPA|[\u02c8m\u026al\u0294n\u0329]}}\n*''Martin'' {{IPA|[\u02c8m\u0251\u0279\u0294n\u0329]}}\n*''mountain'' {{IPA|[\u02c8m\u00e6\u028an\u0294n\u0329]}}\n*''cotton'' {{IPA|[\u02c8k\u02b0\u0251\u0294n\u0329]}}\n*''Latin'' {{IPA|[\u02c8l\u00e6\u0294n\u0329]}}\n\n===Cockney English===\nIn [[Cockney#Typical features|Cockney English]], {{IPA|/t/}} is often realized as a glottal stop {{IPA|[\u0294]}} between vowels, liquids and nasals (notably in the word ''bottle''), a process called [[t-glottalization]].\n\n===German===\nIn [[German language|German]], voiceless stops are commonly debuccalized before syllabic nasals in the following clusters: {{IPA|/mpm\u0329, ltn\u0329, ntn\u0329, \u014bk\u014b\u030d/}}, which thus become {{IPA|[m\u0294m\u0329, l\u0294n\u0329, n\u0294n\u0329, \u014b\u0294\u014b\u030d]}}. For example, {{lang|de|Lumpen}} (\u201crags, tatters\u201d) is pronounced {{IPA|[l\u028am\u0294m\u0329]}}. In some dialects, debuccalization may also occur before syllabic {{IPA|[l\u0329]}}, though this is less common.\n\nVoiced stops are not usually debuccalized. However, many [[Upper German]] and [[East Central German]] dialects merge voiced and unvoiced stops at least word-internally  and these merged consonants will be debuccalized. Thus in [[Bavarian language|Bavarian]], {{lang|bar|Anten}} (\u201cducks\u201d) and {{lang|bar|Anden}} (\u201cAndes\u201d) are both pronounced {{IPA|[\u02c8\u0251n\u0294n\u0329]}}. Speakers are often unaware of this.\n\n==Glottal fricative==\n===Slavey===\nAll coda consonants in [[Slavey language|Slavey]] must be glottal. When a non-glottal consonant would otherwise be positioned in a syllable coda, it debuccalizes to {{IPA|[h]}}:<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Smith|2008|p=527}}</ref>\n*{{IPA|/ts\u2019ad/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[ts\u2019ah]}} ('hat')\n*{{IPA|/xaz/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[xah]}} ('scar')\n*{{IPA|/tl\u2019u\u026e/}} \u2192 {{IPA|[tl\u2019uh]}} ('rope')\n\n===Scots/Scottish English===\nIn some varieties of [[Scots language|Scots]] (and [[Scottish English]]), particularly on the West coast, a non word-final {{IPA|/\u03b8/}} ''th'' shifted to {{IPA|[h]}}, a process called [[th-debuccalization]]. For example, {{IPA|/\u03b8\u026an/}} is realised as {{IPA|[h\u026an]}}.\n\n===Proto-Greek===\nIn [[Proto-Greek language|Proto-Greek]], {{IPA|/s/}} shifted to {{IPA|[h]}} initially and between [[sonorant]]s ([[vowel]]s, [[liquid consonant|liquids]] and [[nasal consonant|nasal]]s).\n* [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] {{wikt-lang|ine-x-proto|*sept\u1e3f\u0325}} \u2192 [[Ancient Greek]] {{transl|grc|hept\u00e1}} ({{wikt-lang|grc|\u1f11\u03c0\u03c4\u03ac}}) \"seven\" (vs. [[Latin]] {{wikt-lang|la|septem}})\n\nIntervocalic {{IPA|/h/}} was lost by the time of [[Ancient Greek]], and vowels in [[hiatus (linguistics)|hiatus]] were [[synaeresis|contracted]] in the [[Attic Greek|Attic]] dialect.\n* post-PIE ''*\u01f5\u00e9nesos'' \u2192 Proto-Greek {{lang|grk-x-proto|*g\u00e9nehos}} \u2192 [[Ionic Greek|Ionic]] {{transl|grc|g\u00e9neos}} ({{lang|grc|\u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03bf\u03c2}}) : [[Attic Greek|Attic]] {{transl|grc|g\u00e9nous}} ({{lang|grc|\u03b3\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2}}) \"of a race\"\n\nBefore a liquid or nasal, an {{IPA|/h/}} was assimilated to the preceding vowel in Attic-Ionic and [[Doric Greek|Doric]] and to the following nasal in [[Aeolic Greek|Aeolic]]. The process is also described as loss of {{IPA|/h/}} and subsequent lengthening of a vowel or consonant to keep the syllable the same [[syllable weight|length]] ([[compensatory lengthening]]).\n* PIE {{wikt-lang|ine-x-proto|*h\u2081\u00e9smi}} \u2192 Proto-Greek {{lang|grk-x-proto|*ehmi}} \u2192 Attic-Ionic {{transl|grc|\u0113m\u00ed}} ({{lang|grc|\u03b5\u1f30\u03bc\u03af}}) : Aeolic {{transl|grc|\u00e9mmi}} ({{lang|grc|\u1f14\u03bc\u03bc\u03b9}}) \"I am\"\n\n===Sanskrit===\nIn [[Sanskrit]], {{IPA|/s/}} becomes {{IPA|[h]}} (written {{transl|sa|\u1e25}} in transliteration) when [[pausa|utterance-final]], e.g., {{transl|sa|k\u0101\u0301mas}} \"erotic love\" becomes {{transl|sa|k\u0101\u0301ma\u1e25}}.\n\n===West Iberian===\n====Spanish====\n{{main|Spanish dialects and varieties#Debuccalization of coda /s/|l1=Spanish dialects and varieties: Debuccalization of coda /s/}}\nA number of [[Spanish language|Spanish]] [[Spanish dialects and varieties|dialects]] debuccalize {{IPA|/s/}} at the [[syllable coda|end]] of a [[syllable]] to {{IPA|[h]}} or {{IPAblink|\u0266}}.\n\n====Galician====\nIn many varieties of [[Galician language|Galician]] as well as in [[Castrapo|Galician-influenced Spanish]], the phoneme {{IPA|/g/}} may debuccalize ({{lang|gl|[[gheada]]}}) to {{IPAblink|h}} in most or all instances, though {{IPAblink|x}} and {{IPAblink|\u0127}} are also possible realizations. There is also an inverse [[hypercorrection]] process of older or less educated Galician speakers replacing the phoneme {{IPAslink|x}} of the Spanish language by {{IPA|[g]}}, what is called {{lang|gl|gueada}}.\n\n====Portuguese====\n[[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] is much less affected by debuccalization, but it is especially notorious in its [[Brazilian Portuguese|Brazilian variety]].\n\nAll over Brazil, the phoneme {{IPA|/\u0281/}} (historically an alveolar trill {{IPA|/r/}} that moved to an uvular position) has a rather long inventory of allophones:{{IPA|[{{IPAplink|r}} {{IPAplink|\u0282|\u027b\u031d\u030a}} {{IPAplink|\u00e7}} {{IPAplink|x}} {{IPAplink|\u0263}} {{IPAplink|\u03c7}} {{IPAplink|\u0281}} {{IPAplink|\u0280}} {{IPAplink|\u0127}} {{IPAplink|h}} {{IPAplink|\u0266}}]}}. Only {{IPAblink|\u0263}} is uncommon. Few dialects, such as {{lang|pt|[[South Region, Brazil|sulista]]}} and {{lang|pt|[[Rio de Janeiro (state)|fluminense]]}}, give preference to voiced allophones; elsewhere, they are common only as coda, before voiced consonants.\n\nIn such dialects, especially among people speaking an educated variety of Portuguese, it is usual for the rhotic coda in the [[Syllable#Rime|syllable rhyme]] to be an alveolar tap, as in European Portuguese and many registers of Spanish, or to be realized as {{IPAblink|\u03c7}} or {{IPAblink|x}}. In the rest of the country, it is generally realized as {{IPAblink|h}}, even among speakers not normally using this allophone or deleting it entirely, as is common in the vernacular.\n\nHowever, in some {{lang|pt|[[Minas Gerais|mineiro]]}}- and {{lang|pt|mineiro}}-influenced {{lang|pt|fluminense}} rural registers, {{IPA|[h]}} is used but as an allophone of {{IPAslink|l}} (rhotic consonants are most often deleted), a {{lang|pt|mar-mal}} merger, instead of the much more common and less stigmatized [[L-vocalization#Portuguese|{{lang|pt|mau-mal|nocat=yes}} merger]] characteristic of all Brazilian urban centers except for those bordering [[Mercosur]] countries, where coda {{IPAblink|\u026b}} was preserved, and the entire [[North Region, Brazil|North]] and [[Northeast Region, Brazil|Northeast]] regions. Its origin is the replacement of indigenous languages and {{lang|pt|[[l\u00edngua geral|l\u00ednguas gerais]]}} by Portuguese,{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}} which created {{IPAblink|\u0279}}, {{IPAblink|\u027b}} and [[r-colored vowel]] as allophones of both {{IPA|/\u027e/}} (now mostly {{IPA|/\u0281/}}) and {{IPA|/l/}} (now mostly {{IPA|[{{IPAplink|w|u\u032f}} ~ {{IPAplink|\u028a|\u028a\u032f}}]}}) phonemes in the coda since Natives could not easily pronounce them ([[caipira dialect]]).{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}} The later Portuguese influence from other regions made those allophones become rarer in some areas, but the {{lang|pt|mar-mal}} merger did not disappear in a few isolated villages and towns.\n\nFinally, many {{lang|pt|fluminense}} registers, especially those of the poor and of the youth, most northern and northeastern dialects, and, to a much minor degree, all other Brazilian dialects, debuccalize {{IPA|/s/}} (that is, {{IPA|[\u0255 ~ \u0291]}}) but less so than in Spanish. However, a {{lang|pt|mar-mas}} merger or even a {{lang|pt|mar-mais}} merger occurs: {{lang|pt|mas mesmo assim}} \"but even so\" or {{lang|pt|mas mesma, sim}} \"though, right, the same (f) one\" {{IPA|[m\u0250\u0266 \u02c8me\u0266m\u0259 \u02c8s\u0129]}}; {{lang|pt|mais}} light \"lighter, more slim\", or also \"less caloric/fatty\" {{IPA|[\u02c8ma\u0266 \u02c8lajt\u0255]}}; {{lang|pt|mas de mim, n\u00e3o}} \"but from me, no\" or {{lang|pt|mais de mim, n\u00e3o}} \"not more from me\" {{IPA|[\u02c8ma\u0266 d\u0291i \u02c8m\u0129 \u02c8n\u025c\u0303w]}}. A coda rhotic in the Brazilian dialects in the [[Centro-Sul]] area is hardly ever glottal, and the debuccalized {{IPA|/s/}} is unlikely to be confused with it.\n\n===Romanian===\nIn the Moldavian dialect of [[Romanian language|Romanian]], {{IPAslink|f}} is debuccalised to {{IPA|[h]}} and so, for example, {{lang|ro|s\u0103 fie}} becomes {{lang|ro|s\u0103 hie}}. The same occurred in [[Old Spanish]], Old [[Gascon language|Gascon]] and [[Old Japanese]] and occurs today in [[Sylheti language |Sylheti]].\n\n===Goidelic Languages===\n{{main|Scottish Gaelic phonology#Lenition and spelling|Irish initial mutations|l1=Scottish Gaelic phonology: Lenition and spelling}}\nIn [[Scottish Gaelic|Scottish]] and [[Irish language|Irish Gaelic]], ''s'' and ''t'' changed by [[lenition]] to {{IPA|[h]}}, spelled ''sh'' and ''th''.\n\n==Loanwords==\nDebuccalization can be a feature of loanword phonology. For example, while [[Korean language|Korean]] allows certain coda obstruents, [[Japanese language|Japanese]] does not. Those consonants realized in Korean as unreleased voiceless stops ({{IPA|[p\u02fa t\u02fa k\u02fa]}}) may be realized in Japanese as glottal stops:<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Whang|2012|p=2}}</ref>\n*{{IPA|[t\u0255uk\u02fa]}} \u2192 {{IPA|[t\u0255u\u0294]}} ('porridge')\n*{{IPA|[mok\u02fa]}} \u2192 {{IPA|[mo\u0294]}} ('neck')\n*{{IPA|[mat\u02fa]}} \u2192 {{IPA|[ma\u0294]}} ('flavor')\n*{{IPA|[tap\u02fa]}}\u2192 {{IPA|[ta\u0294]}} ('tower')\n\nSimilarly, debuccalization can be seen in [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] loans into [[Selayar language|Selayar]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|O'Brien|2012|p=28}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{citation\n|last=O'Brien\n|first=Jeremy Paul\n|year=2012\n|title=An experimental approach to debuccalization and supplementary gestures\n|url=http://escholarship.org/uc/item/1cm694ff\n}}\n*{{citation\n|last=Smith\n|first=Jennifer L.\n|year=2008\n|chapter=X Markedness, faithfulness, positions, and contexts: Lenition and fortition in Optimality Theory\n|editor-last=de Carvalho\n|editor-first=Joaquim Brand\u00e3o\n|editor2-last=Scheer\n|editor2-first=Tobias\n|editor3-last=S\u00e9g\u00e9ral\n|editor3-first=Philippe\n|title=Lenition and Fortition\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ztksXfGwLVgC&dq=\n}}\n*{{citation\n\t|last=Whang \n\t|first=James Dy \n\t|year=2012 \n\t|title=Perception of Illegal Contrasts: Japanese Adaptations of Korean Coda Obstruents \n\t|journal=Proceedings of the 36th Annual Meeting of the Berkeley Linguistics Society \n\t|url=https://files.nyu.edu/jdw412/public/james.whang/main_files/Whang.pdf \n\t|url-status=dead \n\t|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624212809/https://files.nyu.edu/jdw412/public/james.whang/main_files/Whang.pdf \n\t|archivedate=2013-06-24 \n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=wx-4wmfQbVMC&pg=PA123&dq=debuccalization+1990&hl=en&ei=DNE-TuDdCrSisQLbsc0y&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=debuccalization%201990&f=false \"Debuccalization\"] (Chapter 4 of Paul D. Fallon's ''The Synchronic and Diachronic Phonology of Ejectives'' [Routledge, 2001]) gives many other terms that have been proposed for the phenomenon.\n* [http://people.ucsc.edu/~jpobrien/papers/obrien_qe.pdf Debuccalization and supplementary gestures]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n[[Category:Phonology]]\n", "name_user": "2dk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePortuguese", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debuccalization"}
{"title_page": "Charles A. Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Charles A. Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Linden Hill Historic Estate.jpg\n  | caption = Both houses from the exterior\n  | location= 608 Highland Ave., [[Little Falls, Minnesota]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|45|58|15|N|94|21|57|W|source:NRIS2013a|display=inline,title}}\n  | locmapin = Minnesota#United States\n  | built = 1898\n  | builder = A.D. Harrison\n  | architecture = [[Shingle Style]]\n  | added = September 5, 1985\n  | area = {{convert|9|acre|ha}}\n  | refnum = 85001990<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2013a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Charles A. Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses''' are historic houses in [[Little Falls, Minnesota]] that were the homes of Charles A. Weyerhauser and Richard Musser, founders of the [[Pine Tree Lumber Company Office Building|Pine Tree Lumber Company]], a business that played a major role in the growth of Little Falls, as it built a strong lumber industry within the town. The houses were added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on September 5, 1985. The houses are now the location of the '''Linden Hill Historic Estate'''.<ref name=\"nrhpdoc\">{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=85001990}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Charles A. Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|author= |date= |accessdate=April 15, 2020}} With {{NRHP url|id=85001990|photos=y|title=accompanying pictures}}</ref><ref name=\"lhhe\">{{cite web |title=Estate History |url=http://linden-hill.org/estate-history.html |website=Linden Hill Historic Estate |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe houses were the location of a concert by famous pianist [[Van Cliburn]] after he won the inaugural [[International Tchaikovsky Competition]].<ref name=\"lhhe\"/>\n==Description==\nFrom the official nomination form<ref name=\"nrhpdoc\"/>:\n{{Quote\n|text=The Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses occupy a wooded site along the [[Mississippi River]], approximately one-half mile south of the commercial center of Little Falls. The site extends from the river, on the west, to 1st Street Southeast, on the east. 6th Avenue Southeast forms the southern boundary of the site. To the north is an [[oxbow]] of the Mississippi River and, near 1st Street, the [[Burton-Rosenmeier House]]. Both houses are placed alongside an entry drive which forms an extension to Highland Avenue. The houses lie at the top of a bank that drops down to a level plain adjacent to the river. A garage and service building is located at the southern end of this area, which also contains a [[theater|playhouse]], [[gazebo]], and several vine-covered [[trellises]]. Sited on the bank adjoining the oxbow is a [[carriage house]], which contains living quarters on its upper floor. In front of the houses, a lawn extends out to 1st Street. A [[swimming pool|pool]], enclosed by a screened [[pavilion]], is placed near the center of this lawn. A [[tennis court]] is adjacent to the pool. All ground are well-tended, and are planted with a variety of [[shrubs]] and [[flowers]]. [[Trees]] were planted over the entire site to provide a [[forest]]-like setting. Both the Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses were built in the [[Shingle Style]]. The houses were relatively compact in 1898; neither Weyerhaeuser nor Musser were yet married. Each has been enlarged, but the additions that were made have been in keeping with the materials, styling, and proportions of the original houses.\nSimilar materials are used on both houses. Exterior walls are clad primarily with [[shingles]]. The shingles are bellcast at the bottom of the second floor so that the floor line becomes clearly defined. Both are of [[wood-frame]] construction, and have two stories, large [[attics]], and full [[basements]], which are raised so that the main [[living room]]s on the first floor are several feet above ground level. The buildings differ in plan, and in several of their details. The Weyerhaeuser House lies to the south of the Musser House. The main body of the house is rectangular. A front [[porch]], originally open but now enclosed with glass panels, lies in front of a bay that projects out at the center of the main [[facade]]. Beside this entry is a smaller projecting bay that encloses the main stair. Both bays and the porch have [[gabled roof]]s, while the main body of the house is covered with a [[hipped roof]]. The house was extended to the north and south about 1910, with a [[sun room]] being constructed on the south side and a music room on the north. These extension replicate the shingle siding, [[stone]] [[Foundation (engineering)|foundation]]s, and the roof and [[dormer]] configurations of the original house.\n}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://linden-hill.org/ Linden Hill Historic Estate's website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weyerhaeuser, Charles A., and Musser, Richard Drew, Houses}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Minnesota}}\n\t\t\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Morrison County, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1898]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Minnesota]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Charles A. Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Linden Hill Historic Estate.jpg\n  | caption = Both houses from the exterior\n  | location= 608 Highland Ave., [[Little Falls, Minnesota]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|45|58|15|N|94|21|57|W|source:NRIS2013a|display=inline,title}}\n  | locmapin = Minnesota#United States\n  | built = 1898\n  | builder = A.D. Harrison\n  | architecture = [[Shingle Style]]\n  | added = September 5, 1985\n  | area = {{convert|9|acre|ha}}\n  | refnum = 85001990<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2013a}}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Charles A. Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses''' are historic houses in [[Little Falls, Minnesota]] that were the homes of Charles A. Weyerhauser and Richard Musser, founders of the [[Pine Tree Lumber Company Office Building|Pine Tree Lumber Company]], a business that played a major role in the growth of Little Falls, as it built a strong lumber industry within the town. The houses were added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on September 5, 1985. The houses are now the location of the '''Linden Hill Historic Estate'''.<ref name=\"nrhpdoc\">{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=85001990}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Charles A. Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|author= |date= |accessdate=April 15, 2020}} With {{NRHP url|id=85001990|photos=y|title=accompanying pictures}}</ref><ref name=\"lhhe\">{{cite web |title=Estate History |url=http://linden-hill.org/estate-history.html |website=Linden Hill Historic Estate |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe houses were the location of a concert by famous pianist [[Van Cliburn]] after he won the inaugural [[International Tchaikovsky Competition]].<ref name=\"lhhe\"/>\n==Description==\nFrom the official nomination form<ref name=\"nrhpdoc\"/>:\n{{Quote\n|text=The Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses occupy a wooded site along the [[Mississippi River]], approximately one-half mile south of the commercial center of Little Falls. The site extends from the river, on the west, to 1st Street Southeast, on the east. 6th Avenue Southeast forms the southern boundary of the site. To the north is an [[oxbow]] of the Mississippi River and, near 1st Street, the [[Burton-Rosenmeier House]]. Both houses are placed alongside an entry drive which forms an extension to Highland Avenue. The houses lie at the top of a bank that drops down to a level plain adjacent to the river. A garage and service building is located at the southern end of this area, which also contains a [[theater|playhouse]], [[gazebo]], and several vine-covered [[trellises]]. Sited on the bank adjoining the oxbow is a [[carriage house]], which contains living quarters on its upper floor. In front of the houses, a lawn extends out to 1st Street. A [[swimming pool|pool]], enclosed by a screened [[pavillion]], is placed near the center of this lawn. A [[tennis court]] is adjacent to the pool. All ground are well-tended, and are planted with a variety of [[shrubs]] and [[flowers]]. [[Trees]] were planted over the entire site to provide a [[forest]]-like setting. Both the Weyerhaeuser and Musser Houses were built in the [[Shingle Style]]. The houses were relatively compact in 1898; neither Weyerhaeuser nor Musser were yet married. Each has been enlarged, but the additions that were made have been in keeping with the materials, styling, and proportions of the original houses.\nSimilar materials are used on both houses. Exterior walls are clad primarily with [[shingles]]. The shingles are bellcast at the bottom of the second floor so that the floor line becomes clearly defined. Both are of [[wood-frame]] construction, and have two stories, large [[attics]], and full [[basements]], which are raised so that the main [[living room]]s on the first floor are several feet above ground level. The buildings differ in plan, and in several of their details. The Weyerhaeuser House lies to the south of the Musser House. The main body of the house is rectangular. A front [[porch]], originally open but now enclosed with glass panels, lies in front of a bay that projects out at the center of the main [[facade]]. Beside this entry is a smaller projecting bay that encloses the main stair. Both bays and the porch have [[gabled roof]]s, while the main body of the house is covered with a [[hipped roof]]. The house was extended to the north and south about 1910, with a [[sun room]] being constructed on the south side and a music room on the north. These extension replicate the shingle siding, [[stone]] [[Foundation (engineering)|foundation]]s, and the roof and [[dormer]] configurations of the original house.\n}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://linden-hill.org/ Linden Hill Historic Estate's website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weyerhaeuser, Charles A., and Musser, Richard Drew, Houses}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Minnesota}}\n\t\t\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Morrison County, Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1898]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Minnesota]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_A._Weyerhaeuser_and_Musser_Houses"}
